  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the birthday paradox? Calculate how many people you need for a 50% chance of a shared birthday.",
  "response_text": "The birthday paradox, also known as the birthday problem, is a probability problem concerning the probability that at least two people in a group have the same birthday. Contrary to intuition, it shows that with as few as 23 people, there is more than a 50% chance that two or more people will have the same birthday.\n\nTo calculate the number of people needed for a 50% chance of a shared birthday, we can use the complementary probability method. This means we'll find the probability of no shared birthdays and subtract it from 1.\n\nThe probability of no shared birthdays in a group of n people is given by the formula:\n\nP(no shared birthdays) = (365/365)^n * (364/365)^(n-1) * (363/365)^(n-2) * ... * (365-n+1)/365\n\nWe want to find the smallest value of n for which P(no shared birthdays) < 0.5.\n\nUsing a calculator, we can find that when n = 23, P(no shared birthdays) \u2248 0.4921, which means the probability of having at least one shared birthday is approximately 0.5079.\n\nSo, with 23 people, there is a 50.79% chance of a shared birthday.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 10\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 10\nY (Affective Modeling): 0 (This question does not require affective modeling)\nF (Flexibility): 10\nD (Depth of Processing): 10\n---END RATINGS---",
